steps.description:
Pry off the old baseboard carefully with a small pry bar so you can use it to mark and cut the new molding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3e/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3e/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Protect the wall as you pry off old molding so it won't be damaged. Use a piece of scrap wood between the wall and the pry bar. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You may be able to cut off damaged areas of molding and re-use part of the old molding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove any nails that pull through the old molding and are left in the wall. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using the old molding to make a template for corner cuts and cuts around outlets or other obstructions is ideal. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/20/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/20/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make a template out of stiff paper or cardboard for difficult cuts if there is no old molding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Molding pieces should end at a wall stud. Try to cut pieces so that you join two pieces at a wall stud. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Allow for the depth of both pieces of the molding when butting two pieces together at a corner. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/99/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/99/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have a miter box you can miter the corners (cut at an angle) so they fit together neatly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure cuts where molding will meet another piece in a line are perfectly straight to avoid gaps between pieces. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure any flooring and wall coverings such as wallpaper or paneling are in place and any painting is done before installing the molding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Work with one wall at a time. Start at one corner and fit all the pieces in place. Mark the backs of molding pieces if there are several for that wall in the order they will be installed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

While you are fitting the molding, look for studs to nail it into and lightly mark them in the area just above where the molding will sit. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/14/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/14/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The molding should sit right on top of the flooring. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/12/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/12/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use finishing nails about 2”(5.1 cm) in length. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try to get nails into a stud. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Place the nails about 18” (45.7 cm) apart or at each wall stud. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-New-Baseboard-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
